<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>keychain-access-groups</key>
	<array>
		<string>$(AppIdentifierPrefix)com.alexesterkin.sortlist</string>
	</array>
	<!--
	  NOTE on Associated Domains: we briefly added them here in Build 16,
	  hoping to back the iOS Universal Link path with the SE having matching
	  entitlements. The build failed at the codesign step with:
	      Provisioning profile "[…SortlistShareExtension…]" doesn't
	      include the com.apple.developer.associated-domains entitlement.
	  Same class of issue as the keychain-access-groups saga: Associated
	  Domains is a capability that has to be enabled on the App ID in
	  Apple Developer portal before the provisioning profile will grant it,
	  and EAS doesn't auto-sync it. Functionally it's also unnecessary:
	  the main app's associated-domains entitlement (already in the
	  signed main-app binary) is what makes iOS route incoming Universal
	  Links into our app. The SE doesn't need its own entitlement to
	  call extensionContext.open() on an HTTPS URL — iOS dispatches the
	  URL to whichever app's AASA matches, which is the main app.
	  Leaving the entry commented here as the historical record. If we
	  ever do want SE-level Universal Link HANDLING (rare; we don't
	  currently), enable the capability on the SE's App ID in Apple
	  Developer portal first.
	-->
</dict>
</plist>
